\frame{\frametitle{Harmonic Analysis and Number Theory (1964--1973)}

{\color{ZurichBlue} Results in the following areas:} 
\begin{itemize}
\item Ditkin sets.
\item Diophantine approximations.
\end{itemize}

\vspace*{0.15cm}

{\color{ZurichBlue} Definition (Meyer; 1972):} 
A set $\Lambda \subset \R^n$ is a {\color{green} model set}, if there
exist a finite set $F \subset \R^n$ and a constant $C > 0$ such that
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(1)] $\Lambda - \Lambda \subset \Lambda + F$, and
\item[(2)] $\inf_{\lambda \in \Lambda} |x-\lambda| \le C \;$ for all $x \in \R^n$.
\end{enumerate}

\vspace*{0.25cm}\pause

{\color{ZurichBlue} Theorem (Meyer; 1972):}

If $\Lambda$ is a model set and if $\theta \Lambda \subset \Lambda$, then $\theta$ is a Pisot or a Salem number.\\
{\it\small (A {\color{green}Pisot number} is a real algebraic integer greater than 1 all of whose Galois conjugates 
are less than 1 in absolute value.)}

\vspace*{0.25cm}

{\color{ZurichBlue} Impact:}
Paved the road to the mathematical theory of {\color{green}quasicrystals}.\\
$\leadsto$ Non-period patterns in quasicrystals can be identified\\ \hspace*{0.43cm} with specific model sets.
%\item Predates and impacted first constructions of {\color{green}Penrose tilings}.

