\begin{frame}\frametitle{Meyer's Motivation}

{\color{ZurichBlue} Wavelet transform:}
$$
\mathcal{W}(f)(u,v) = 2^{u/2} \langle f, g_{u,v}\rangle = 2^{u/2} \int_{-\infty}^\infty f(x) g(2^{u} x - v) dx,
$$
for $f \in L^2(\R)$.

{\color{ZurichBlue} Reconstruction and energy preservation:}
Under certain assumptions on $g$:
$$
\|f\|_2= \|\mathcal{W} f\|_{2},
$$
and $f$ can be uniquely recovered from $\mathcal{W}(f)$ by
$$
f(x) = \int \int 2^{u/2} g(2^{u} x - v) \mathcal{W}(f)(u,v) du dv.
$$
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}\frametitle{Calderon's Reproducing Formula}
{\color{ZurichBlue} Meyer and operators:} 
Yves Meyer has been working on singular integral operators until this point.

{\color{ZurichBlue} Calderon's identity:}
If $g$ satisfies an admissibility condition, then, with $g_u(x) = u^{-1}g(x/u)$, we have for all $f\in L^2(\R)$ 
$$
{\color{green}f = \int f * g_u *g_u du/u},
$$
where $f*g(x) = \int f(y) g(x-y)dy$. 

Compare with the reproducing formula of Morlet's wavelets:
\color{green}
\begin{align*}
  f(x)  &= \int \int 2^{u/2} g(2^{u} x - v) \mathcal{W}(f)(u,v) dv du\\
	&= \int \int 2^{u/2} g(2^{u} x - v) \int f(y) 2^{u/2} g(2^{u} y - v) dy dv du.
\end{align*}
\color{black}
\end{frame}

