\begin{frame}\frametitle{Gabor Systems}

To understand the research on wavelet bases it is impotant to understand what was the standard then.

{\color{ZurichBlue} Gabor systems:}
$$
\Gamma_{\alpha, \beta}(g) = \{g_{n,m}(x) :=  e^{2 \pi i \alpha n x} g(x-\beta m), \quad m,n \in \Z\},
$$
were $\alpha, \beta >0$, $g\in L^2(\R)$. 
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width = 0.2\textwidth]{images/Gabor3.png} \ \includegraphics[width = 0.2\textwidth]{images/Gabor2.png} \ \includegraphics[width = 0.2\textwidth]{images/Gabor1.png}
\end{center}

\

{\color{ZurichBlue} Typical question:}
What conditions do we need to impose on $\alpha, \beta, g$ so that $\Gamma_{\alpha, \beta}(g)$ is an orthonormal basis?

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}\frametitle{Balian-Low Theorem}

{\color{ZurichBlue} Orthonomal bases of Gabor systems:}
It turns out all orthonormal bases or Gabor systems have {\color{green}bad time-frequency localization}.

\medskip

{\color{ZurichBlue} {Theorem:} (Balian-Low Theorem)}\\
 If $\alpha, \beta >0$, $g\in L^2(\R)$ and $\Gamma_{\alpha, \beta}(g)$ is an orthonormal basis, then
 \begin{align*}
  \int x^2 |g(x)|^2 dx= \infty \quad \text{ or }   \int \xi^2 |\hat{g}(\xi)|^2 d\xi= \infty.
 \end{align*}


\medskip

Meyer wanted to prove the same result for orthonormal wavelet bases...

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[t]{The Meyer Wavelet}
... but he "failed":

\medskip

Meyer found the following function $\psi$:
\begin{align}
 \hat{\psi}=\begin{cases}
             (2\pi)^{-1/2}{\color{green}e^{i\xi/2}}\sin\left[\frac{\pi}{2}{\color{green}\vartheta\left(\frac{3}{2\pi}\abs{\xi}-1
             \right)}\right],& \text{ if }\frac{2\pi}{3}\le\abs{\xi}\le\frac{4\pi}{3}\vspace*{0.3cm}\\
             (2\pi)^{-1/2}{\color{green}e^{i\xi/2}}\cos\left[\frac{\pi}{2}{\color{green}\vartheta\left(\frac{3}{4\pi}\abs{\xi}-1
             \right)}\right],& \text{ if }\frac{4\pi}{3}\le\abs{\xi}\le\frac{8\pi}{3}\vspace*{0.3cm}\\
             0&\text{ otherwise},
            \end{cases}
\end{align}

\only<1>{
