\begin{frame}\frametitle{Approximation with Neural Networks}

A common model for neural networks is given by

\begin{multicols}{2}
\begin{itemize}
 \item $d\in \N$: dimension of the input layer,
 \item $L$: number of layers,
 \item $N$ number of neurons,
 \item $\rho: \R \to \R$ rectifier,
 \item $W_\ell:\R^{N_{\ell-1}} \to \R^{N_{\ell}}$, $\ell = 1, \dots, L$: Affine linear maps.
\end{itemize}
\columnbreak

\

\includegraphics[width = 0.4\textwidth]{images/dnnExpl.eps}
\end{multicols}
Then $\Phi: \R^d \to \R^{N_L}$ given by
\[
\Phi(x) = W_L\rho( W_{L-1}\rho( \dots \rho (W_{1}(x))), \quad x\in \R^d,
\]
is called a {\color{green}neural network}. 
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}\frametitle{Approximation with Neural Networks}
{\color{ZurichBlue} Approximation properties:}
\textit{How well can an arbitrary function be approximated by a neural network?}

\

{\color{ZurichBlue} Universal approximation:}
For any continuous function $f:K\to \R$ and any $\epsilon>0$ there exists a neural network approximating $f$ up to an error $\epsilon$. [Cybenko; 1989, Hornik et al.; 1991].

\

{\color{ZurichBlue} Rate of approximation:}
It is unclear how complex the neural network needs to be.
\end{frame}

